Hi Ditch -

FreightCar America Inc. (RAIL)
http://www.freightcaramerica.com/
2011 Annual Report:
http://www.freightcaramerica.com/PDFs/FCA_Annual_Report_2011.pdf

You might want to look at RAIL. I have no position but have been tracking the
company for the last 6 months. They are a pure play for U.S. rail car
maintenance and manufacturing but I have not really compared them to GMT.

GMT is huge w/ operations all over the world. I really liked their exposure in
the Natural Gas Compression Equipment Leasing space but it is very small
compared to their other operations.

RAIL's order book is up and produce a wide variety of new rail car and
suspension systems. The company also has a large repair and service business
too. Financially, RAIL's forward PE is under 10, has no long term debt and pays
a dividend that currently yields about 1%. Their PE is 90% of the industry 5yr
rate so their is the possibility for PE expansion. Still, ROE of 2.5% is not
that exciting for me.
http://finance.yahoo.com/q/ks?s=RAIL+Key+Statistics

EPS are heading higher after plunging negative in the 2008/2009 market crash.

<img src='http://www.advfn.com/p.php?pid=us_fin_graph&symbol=RAIL&type=5'>

Tangible BV is $15.45/share.

I prefer those companies that have a larger leasing segment that generate much
larger cash flows. For that cash flow, then you must accept a much larger debt
load. In 2011, RAIL did form a new railcar parts, repair, maintenance and
maintenance management business. As this segment of their service business
grows and they land more annual service contracts that provides their customers
better "life cycle" fixed maintenance stability, maybe they can offer more
customers a "buy" & "annual service" option contract rather than do the
traditional lease back contracts.
